01:02:26.507 --> 01:02:30.044
Having had only marginal success
on NBC for three years,

01:02:30.077 --> 01:02:33.181
the show took on
new life in syndication.

01:02:33.215 --> 01:02:37.086
Gradually, the show and its
audience found each other.

01:02:37.119 --> 01:02:40.556
By the mid '70s, it was
becoming a media event.

01:02:40.588 --> 01:02:43.324
Thousands and thousands
of new devotees

01:02:43.358 --> 01:02:44.994
sat in front of their TV sets

01:02:45.027 --> 01:02:48.998
memorizing each episode's
dialogue word for word.

01:02:49.030 --> 01:02:54.135
Risk... risk is our business.

01:02:54.168 --> 01:02:56.172
"That's what this
starship is all about.

01:02:56.204 --> 01:03:00.074
"That's why we're aboard her.

01:03:00.108 --> 01:03:05.314
"Dr. McCoy is right to point out
the enormous risk involved

01:03:05.347 --> 01:03:08.984
"with interaction between
any two alien species,

01:03:09.016 --> 01:03:11.419
but the potential... "

01:03:14.856 --> 01:03:17.525
There's something that I became aware
of in doing my research very recently

01:03:17.559 --> 01:03:19.195
called The Slash Fantasy,

01:03:19.228 --> 01:03:22.164
the Kirk-Spock slash fantasy.

01:03:22.197 --> 01:03:26.035
And there's a phenomenal
edited video on YouTube.

01:03:26.068 --> 01:03:28.838
And some fan, somebody's
taken a lot of footage

01:03:28.871 --> 01:03:32.273
of Kirk and Spock out of context
from "The Original Series"

01:03:32.306 --> 01:03:35.476
to show this homo-erotic
relationship between them,

01:03:35.510 --> 01:03:38.281
and it's pretty damn compelling.

01:03:49.157 --> 01:03:53.362
At conventions,
I saw slash zines

01:03:53.394 --> 01:03:56.931
with illustrations done
by very good artists

01:03:56.965 --> 01:04:02.538
and they were much, much more
explicit between Kirk and Spock.

01:04:02.570 --> 01:04:06.275
It's a matter
of who is looking at it,

01:04:06.307 --> 01:04:07.675
from what perspective,

01:04:07.710 --> 01:04:14.983
and from the perspective of gay
people seeing that is eye opening.

01:04:15.016 --> 01:04:19.487
They see the gay passion,
the gay attraction,

01:04:19.521 --> 01:04:24.093
and the gay anguish
depicted in those scenes.

01:04:35.670 --> 01:04:38.273
At my first convention in 1972,

01:04:38.306 --> 01:04:40.174
I walked into a hall so crowded

01:04:40.208 --> 01:04:42.644
the thunderous wall of
noise that greeted me

01:04:42.677 --> 01:04:44.946
took me completely by surprise.

01:04:44.980 --> 01:04:49.184
For several seconds, I literally could
not speak because of the emotion.

01:04:49.217 --> 01:04:53.055
One of the things that I really
respect about your dad was,

01:04:53.088 --> 01:04:55.024
I guess, his love
and affection for the fans

01:04:55.056 --> 01:04:58.359
and how he always
had time and energy.

01:04:58.393 --> 01:05:00.396
You know, going to conventions
and meeting people...

01:05:00.429 --> 01:05:02.331
You know, I'm blown away

01:05:02.364 --> 01:05:08.137
by how much love
there is for your father.

01:05:08.170 --> 01:05:10.072
It was an entirely new concept,

01:05:10.105 --> 01:05:14.376
this gathering of fans to
celebrate "Trek" for a weekend.

01:05:14.409 --> 01:05:16.144
The organizers crossed
their fingers

01:05:16.177 --> 01:05:19.248
and hoped for 500 attendees.

01:05:19.280 --> 01:05:21.384
They got 3,000.

01:05:22.583 --> 01:05:25.420
We went
to one "Star Trek" convention.

01:05:25.454 --> 01:05:28.624
I think it was in LA,
but I'm not sure.

01:05:28.657 --> 01:05:29.692
I think you're right.

01:05:29.724 --> 01:05:31.960
Yeah, it was a wild place.

01:05:31.994 --> 01:05:33.729
I remember them having
to get us out the back door.

01:05:33.762 --> 01:05:34.730
Right.

01:05:34.762 --> 01:05:38.232
Okay.
What was that like?

01:05:38.266 --> 01:05:39.201
Wild.

01:06:02.257 --> 01:06:04.092
I think "Star Trek" fans have
sort of pioneered

01:06:04.126 --> 01:06:06.195
the whole cos-play culture
which now exists

01:06:06.228 --> 01:06:07.695
where, you know, you go
to any convention,

01:06:07.728 --> 01:06:10.631
and people are dressed up
as a multitude of things

01:06:10.664 --> 01:06:15.070
from the most obscure
to the most popular.

01:06:15.103 --> 01:06:21.210
I've been blown away going to now these
conventions for a number of years,

01:06:21.242 --> 01:06:24.746
seeing what people are able,
and willing, and, you know,

01:06:24.780 --> 01:06:27.249
what they commit
to dress up as and do,

01:06:27.282 --> 01:06:29.485
and it's unbelievable.

01:06:29.518 --> 01:06:31.619
We thought they were crazy.

01:06:39.628 --> 01:06:42.097
I'm here. I'm really here.
I can't believe it.

01:06:42.130 --> 01:06:45.201
My first "Star Trek" convention.
Watch your back. Here we go.

01:06:49.737 --> 01:06:51.706
So much stuff.

01:06:55.077 --> 01:06:56.345
Really cool.

01:07:09.356 --> 01:07:12.126
Spock, status report?

01:07:12.159 --> 01:07:15.696
Pollux IV, class M type planet,
oxygen-nitrogen atmosphere.

01:07:15.730 --> 01:07:19.134
Sensors indicate no life forms.

01:07:19.166 --> 01:07:23.337
In all respects,
quite ordinary, Captain.

01:07:23.371 --> 01:07:26.508
Bobak, I want you to tell me a little bit
about your history with "Star Trek",

01:07:26.541 --> 01:07:28.009
how it's affected your life.

01:07:28.043 --> 01:07:30.846
I would say it's probably one of the
biggest reasons why I work at NASA.

01:07:30.878 --> 01:07:33.382
I mean, honestly, like, you
know, seeing this "Star Trek,"

01:07:33.414 --> 01:07:35.583
you know, this vision
of the future

01:07:35.617 --> 01:07:39.388
is one of the reasons
why I work there today.

01:07:39.420 --> 01:07:44.125
Seeing a future where people from all
different cultures and backgrounds

01:07:44.159 --> 01:07:44.992
were working together.

01:07:45.027 --> 01:07:46.461
You know,
the betterment of humanity.

01:07:46.494 --> 01:07:50.364
I think that was a vision of the
future that I wanted to help create.

01:07:50.398 --> 01:07:53.402
If "Star Trek" was the vision of the
future that I wanted to create,

01:07:53.434 --> 01:07:57.172
Spock was the internalization of the
kind of person that I felt like I was.

01:07:57.204 --> 01:07:59.240
You know, as someone
who was from two cultures,

01:07:59.273 --> 01:08:01.710
you know, Iranian father,
an American mother,

01:08:01.742 --> 01:08:05.547
I saw in Spock, you know,
that same conflict, I guess,

01:08:05.579 --> 01:08:07.715
of, "Which one am I?
Am I both?

01:08:07.748 --> 01:08:10.651
Is there a happy
medium of the two?"

01:08:10.684 --> 01:08:14.523
But also at the same time,
I saw that he was accepted

01:08:14.556 --> 01:08:17.826
by his, you know, colleagues.

01:08:17.859 --> 01:08:20.129
Spock stood for a lot
of different things.

01:08:20.162 --> 01:08:23.532
He stood for
intelligence, integrity.

01:08:23.564 --> 01:08:26.902
He stood for the idea of
really searching for truth,

01:08:26.935 --> 01:08:29.571
for figuring out
how things really work.

01:08:29.604 --> 01:08:31.874
That is the underpinning
of science, really.

01:08:31.907 --> 01:08:36.912
So I think for a lot of people, Spock
was representative of science itself,

01:08:36.944 --> 01:08:41.149
of using the human mind to overcome
kind of the forces of chaos

01:08:41.182 --> 01:08:42.818
and make sense of things.

01:08:42.850 --> 01:08:45.420
That really resonates with a lot
of people here, I would say.

01:08:45.453 --> 01:08:46.453
It certainly did with me.

01:08:46.488 --> 01:08:49.291
And I knew the minute
I read "Star Trek" books,

01:08:49.323 --> 01:08:52.260
that was the character I most
wanted to emulate with my career.

01:08:52.292 --> 01:08:55.162
Spock was a scientist.

01:08:55.197 --> 01:08:58.367
Now, for me, I knew I liked
science before "Star Trek."

01:08:58.399 --> 01:09:02.837
So Spock and I resonated,
I think...

01:09:02.871 --> 01:09:08.341
in a way that surely helped,
but didn't initiate my interest.

01:09:08.376 --> 01:09:12.581
But I wonder if the slow
but real appreciation

01:09:12.613 --> 01:09:14.916
for what science is
and why it matters

01:09:14.948 --> 01:09:17.786
that I see manifesting today,

01:09:17.819 --> 01:09:20.221
whether it owes its origin

01:09:20.255 --> 01:09:22.524
to that series,
to that character.

01:09:28.229 --> 01:09:30.298
-Are you a "Star Trek" fan?
-Yes.

01:09:30.332 --> 01:09:32.801
-How long have you been a fan?
-A hundred years.

01:09:32.832 --> 01:09:35.371
A hundred years
"Star Trek" fan, okay.

01:09:37.837 --> 01:09:40.442
You've had your own
connection to "Star Trek."

01:09:40.475 --> 01:09:42.743
You've directed
"Star Trek" episodes.

01:09:42.777 --> 01:09:46.247
But before that, you were
an entertainment attorney.

01:09:46.279 --> 01:09:48.417
What was that all about? What got
you into that in the first place?

01:09:48.448 --> 01:09:52.287
You know, it's very difficult when
you are the son of a celebrity

01:09:52.319 --> 01:09:55.657
and somebody who becomes
a pop culture icon,

01:09:55.689 --> 01:09:57.759
to try to create
your own identity,

01:09:57.792 --> 01:09:59.861
to find out who you
are in essence.

01:09:59.894 --> 01:10:03.298
And so, this was my way of
really creating my own path.

01:10:03.331 --> 01:10:05.833
He was very proud of the fact
that I went to law school,

01:10:05.867 --> 01:10:08.003
and I started practicing law.

01:10:08.036 --> 01:10:10.005
But after seven years
of practicing,

01:10:10.037 --> 01:10:12.506
it became very clear to me
that this was not something

01:10:12.539 --> 01:10:14.009
I wanted to do
for the rest of my life.

01:10:14.042 --> 01:10:18.579
I didn't have the passion for it
that I thought was important.

01:10:18.613 --> 01:10:20.481
That was really Dad's
whole philosophy was

01:10:20.515 --> 01:10:22.484
you have to have a passion
for what you do.

01:10:22.516 --> 01:10:25.554
Otherwise, it's just work,
and it's not fulfilling.

01:10:25.587 --> 01:10:30.359
My dad was very sympathetic about
my desire to make a career change

01:10:30.391 --> 01:10:33.327
and even helped me,
trained me as a director.

01:10:33.360 --> 01:10:35.730
He and I actually
made an episode

01:10:35.764 --> 01:10:37.199
of "The Outer Limits" together.

01:10:37.231 --> 01:10:41.403
We were remaking an episode that he
was originally in in the early '60s

01:10:41.435 --> 01:10:43.471
in which he had
a supporting role.

01:10:43.505 --> 01:10:46.408
Your design and your construction
are nothing short of genius,

01:10:46.440 --> 01:10:49.911
but even you must understand
that you're basically a takeoff

01:10:49.944 --> 01:10:54.316
on the thoughts and feelings that
Dr. Link programmed into you.

01:10:54.349 --> 01:10:58.886
A man suffers, a man bleeds,
a man has a soul.

01:10:58.920 --> 01:11:01.623
I could snap your neck
as if it were a toothpick.

01:11:01.655 --> 01:11:04.792
In that sense, you're right.
I'm not like most men.

01:11:04.826 --> 01:11:07.762
But like most men,
I choose not to.

01:11:07.796 --> 01:11:09.565
Let me go.

01:11:14.802 --> 01:11:17.738
The Motion Picture"

01:11:17.771 --> 01:11:22.476
rightly begins in London where my
wife and I were vacationing in 1975.

01:11:22.510 --> 01:11:26.948
We went to see Henry Fonda who was
performing on stage in "Darrow."

01:11:26.980 --> 01:11:29.951
After the performance, we joined
him and his wife for dinner.

01:11:29.984 --> 01:11:32.321
At some point during
the conversation, Henry said,

01:11:32.354 --> 01:11:34.056
"You know, Leonard,
I hope you're being paid

01:11:34.088 --> 01:11:36.557
for all those billboards
around town."

01:11:36.591 --> 01:11:39.027
"What billboards, Henry?"

01:11:39.060 --> 01:11:43.465
"Do you mean to tell me you don't know
about all those Heineken billboards?"

01:11:43.497 --> 01:11:46.867
Now, I'd seen my Spock image
used commercially before,

01:11:46.900 --> 01:11:49.037
such as on a box of
Kellogg's Corn Flakes.

01:11:49.069 --> 01:11:53.107
I'd been amused by it, finding
it campy and even flattering.

01:11:53.140 --> 01:11:55.777
Once "Star Trek" was canceled,

01:11:55.810 --> 01:12:01.016
Paramount had no legal right to license
my likeness from that time on.

01:12:01.048 --> 01:12:03.685
So not only had Paramount
been marketing me as Spock

01:12:03.717 --> 01:12:06.755
for almost 10 years
without the right to do so,

01:12:06.787 --> 01:12:11.592
for the last five of those 10, they
hadn't sent me any of the proceeds.

01:12:11.626 --> 01:12:14.796
I wound up having
to file a lawsuit.

01:12:14.828 --> 01:12:16.931
They wanted to make this movie.

01:12:16.965 --> 01:12:19.000
And Bob Weiss had it
in his contract

01:12:19.033 --> 01:12:21.370
that they would make their best
efforts to get me in the movie.

01:12:21.403 --> 01:12:23.105
And my agent would
call me and say,

01:12:23.137 --> 01:12:24.506
"They wanna talk to you about the 'Star
Trek' movie." And I would say...

01:12:24.539 --> 01:12:27.943
"When we settle the lawsuit, I'll
talk about acting in their movie,"

01:12:27.975 --> 01:12:30.746
because I thought
that's my leverage.

01:12:30.779 --> 01:12:32.647
So that went on for some time.

01:12:32.680 --> 01:12:36.885
And... finally, I got a call

01:12:36.917 --> 01:12:38.686
from a guy who introduced
himself to me.

01:12:38.720 --> 01:12:40.622
He said, "My name
is Jeff Katzenberg,

01:12:40.654 --> 01:12:42.724
and I've just gone to
work for Paramount."

01:12:42.756 --> 01:12:47.161
And I was acting in "Equus" on
Broadway at the time in New York.

01:12:47.194 --> 01:12:50.097
So there goes little Jeffrey
off trotting to New York...

01:12:50.131 --> 01:12:53.969
...to say to him, "You've got
to put the ears back on."

01:12:54.002 --> 01:12:55.937
So I went, and I saw the show,

01:12:55.970 --> 01:12:58.106
and after the show,
we went to Joe Allen's.

01:12:58.139 --> 01:13:02.644
I said to him, "We're going
to make the movie.

01:13:02.676 --> 01:13:04.779
"Those ears are going on.

01:13:04.813 --> 01:13:08.949
"They're either going on you, or they're
actually going to go on somebody else,

01:13:08.983 --> 01:13:11.019
"but they are going to go on.

01:13:11.051 --> 01:13:16.056
And how badly will you feel
when you didn't put them on?"

01:13:16.090 --> 01:13:20.729
The big leverage that he always
had beginning with these movies

01:13:20.761 --> 01:13:24.932
was that Paramount Pictures
needed him,

01:13:24.966 --> 01:13:27.936
and they couldn't make a "Star
Trek" movie without him.

01:13:27.969 --> 01:13:29.471
Finally, my lawyer called.

01:13:29.503 --> 01:13:34.208
"Look, Paramount is actually showing
some willingness to reach an agreement.

01:13:34.242 --> 01:13:37.212
"Will you read the script
if they settle the lawsuit?"

01:13:37.244 --> 01:13:38.947
"Yes."

01:13:38.979 --> 01:13:41.916
Four days later, on a Friday
evening, the lawsuit settled.

01:13:41.949 --> 01:13:44.685
My lawyer came to my
house with a check.

01:13:44.719 --> 01:13:47.122
An hour later,
the script arrived.

01:13:47.154 --> 01:13:50.192
I sat down and read it
through that night.

01:13:50.225 --> 01:13:51.993
Leonard Nimoy was
the last person

01:13:52.025 --> 01:13:56.497
to join the movie cast and was
asked why he was a hold out.

01:13:56.530 --> 01:13:58.065
I don't think it was
a question of hold out.

01:13:58.099 --> 01:14:02.103
We've had a long and...
complicated relationship,

01:14:02.136 --> 01:14:04.973
I mean, Paramount and myself,
for the last couple of years.

01:14:05.006 --> 01:14:06.842
And probably the thing
that took the most time

01:14:06.875 --> 01:14:09.043
is the fact that
the mail service

01:14:09.077 --> 01:14:11.814
between here and Vulcan
is still pretty slow.

01:14:19.787 --> 01:14:21.457
Spock.

01:14:23.591 --> 01:14:27.628
Making that first movie was
very, very dis-spiriting,

01:14:27.662 --> 01:14:29.130
very depressing.

01:14:29.162 --> 01:14:31.165
We had a bad script,
bad script.

01:14:31.198 --> 01:14:33.134
It just never worked.
It was always a struggle

01:14:33.167 --> 01:14:37.039
to try to figure out how to bring
some life to this... project.

01:14:38.171 --> 01:14:43.744
And, we did our best,
but I never...

01:14:43.778 --> 01:14:48.750
The pendulum swung completely
when that first movie came along

01:14:48.783 --> 01:14:52.621
from being an actor and
character-oriented "Star Trek"

01:14:52.654 --> 01:14:54.689
to an effects-oriented
"Star Trek."

01:14:54.721 --> 01:14:56.791
And the feeling was, "We
didn't have the money before.

01:14:56.823 --> 01:14:59.059
Now we've got the money, we've got
to give them a big effects movie."

01:14:59.092 --> 01:15:01.695
So it was all about the ship, the ship,
and this effect, and that effect,

01:15:01.729 --> 01:15:02.865
and we're going
through this thing.

01:15:06.634 --> 01:15:08.237
Now, we're going
through that thing.

01:15:10.003 --> 01:15:12.774
Nothing about the characters.

01:15:12.806 --> 01:15:16.911
So it was frustrating, and
depressing, and, very painful.

01:15:31.359 --> 01:15:32.628
Khan.

01:15:33.661 --> 01:15:36.230
Khan!

01:15:36.264 --> 01:15:41.036
In "Star Trek II," the lure that
Harve Bennett gave him was,

01:15:41.069 --> 01:15:44.306
"You're going to have the greatest
death scene of all time."

01:15:44.338 --> 01:15:46.041
Spock, no!

01:15:54.649 --> 01:15:56.718
I thought that was
the final "Star Trek" movie,

01:15:56.751 --> 01:15:58.686
and when they said to me,
"How about a death scene?"

01:15:58.720 --> 01:16:00.588
I thought, "Why not? If this
is the end of 'Star Trek,'

01:16:00.622 --> 01:16:02.657
"let's get out in a blaze of
glory saving the Enterprise.

01:16:02.689 --> 01:16:05.626
You know,
be a hero and die."

01:16:09.697 --> 01:16:11.766
Live long...

01:16:12.634 --> 01:16:13.902
and prosper.

01:16:32.420 --> 01:16:35.757
Sooner than I realized,
it was over.

01:16:35.789 --> 01:16:37.626
No.

01:16:37.658 --> 01:16:41.128
I stripped off the ears,
the makeup, the uniform,

01:16:41.162 --> 01:16:43.632
and so Spock
gradually disappeared,

01:16:43.664 --> 01:16:46.768
leaving behind
only Leonard Nimoy.

01:16:48.703 --> 01:16:51.640
Never again the raised eyebrow.

01:16:51.672 --> 01:16:55.777
Never again the delicious
teasing of the irascible doctor

01:16:55.810 --> 01:17:00.048
or the offering of logic to my
impetuous friend and captain.

01:17:00.081 --> 01:17:03.318
Never again the mind meld,
the neck pinch,

01:17:03.350 --> 01:17:05.819
or the Vulcan salute
and blessing,

01:17:05.853 --> 01:17:08.023
live long and prosper.

01:17:08.055 --> 01:17:13.160
I asked myself,
"What have I done?"

01:17:13.194 --> 01:17:15.864
Well, of course, they put in a little
footage at the end of the movie

01:17:15.896 --> 01:17:19.134
that suggested that this might
not be the end of Spock.

01:17:19.167 --> 01:17:22.671
I'm sorry, Doctor. I have no
time to discuss this logically.

01:17:27.007 --> 01:17:28.409
Remember.

01:17:28.443 --> 01:17:29.744
And they came to me,
sure enough,

01:17:29.777 --> 01:17:31.680
after the picture opened
and did business,

01:17:31.712 --> 01:17:34.014
and they called me
in for a meeting.

01:17:34.047 --> 01:17:35.916
They said, "We'd like to know if you'd like
to be involved in another 'Star Trek' movie?"

01:17:35.949 --> 01:17:37.719
And I said,
"Yes, I'd like to direct it."

01:17:37.752 --> 01:17:42.390
I remember distinctly one night
I got a phone call from him.

01:17:42.422 --> 01:17:45.059
And he said he'd been on the
phone with Michael Eisner,

01:17:45.092 --> 01:17:48.430
and that Michael Eisner was trying
to talk him out of directing,

01:17:48.462 --> 01:17:50.864
making his directing debut

01:17:50.898 --> 01:17:54.703
directing himself in a
feature film and so forth.

01:17:54.735 --> 01:17:59.206
And he was asking me...
He was soliciting my advice.

01:17:59.239 --> 01:18:02.176
I said, "Well,
it's really very simple.

01:18:02.210 --> 01:18:07.815
Are you prepared to let this
ship sail without you?"

01:18:07.849 --> 01:18:09.284
And he said, "Absolutely."

01:18:09.317 --> 01:18:12.220
I said, "Then sit tight You're
going to direct the movie."

01:18:12.252 --> 01:18:15.856
My Lord, the ship appears
to be deserted.

01:18:15.890 --> 01:18:18.359
How can that be?
They're hiding.

01:18:18.391 --> 01:18:22.229
Yes, sir, but the bridge seems
to be run by a computer.

01:18:22.262 --> 01:18:23.731
It is the only thing speaking.

01:18:23.765 --> 01:18:25.167
Speaking?

01:18:26.266 --> 01:18:27.868
Let me hear.

01:18:27.902 --> 01:18:33.507
Nine, eight, seven, six, five...

01:18:33.541 --> 01:18:35.342
Get out!

01:18:35.376 --> 01:18:36.911
Get out of there!

01:18:36.944 --> 01:18:39.748
I got a call before the movie
opened from Jeff Katzenberg,

01:18:39.780 --> 01:18:42.283
who was head of production
at Paramount at the time,

01:18:42.315 --> 01:18:44.184
and he said, "We want you
to make another one."

01:18:44.217 --> 01:18:47.087
And I said, "You know, this one that
I just finished, 'Star Trek III',"

01:18:47.121 --> 01:18:49.457
I said, "They had a pretty
tight choke chain on me,

01:18:49.489 --> 01:18:50.992
"controlling what I was doing,

01:18:51.024 --> 01:18:52.359
"and making me answer
for everything,

01:18:52.393 --> 01:18:55.430
and explain everything that I was
doing, and justify everything."

01:18:55.462 --> 01:18:57.798
And he said... I'll never forget.
He was wonderful.

01:18:57.832 --> 01:18:59.467
He said,
"The training wheels are off.

01:18:59.500 --> 01:19:02.936
We want you to make
your 'Star Trek' movie."

01:19:02.970 --> 01:19:05.774
Well, if it isn't Robin Hood
and Friar Tuck.

01:19:06.974 --> 01:19:08.476
Where are you fellas heading?

01:19:09.911 --> 01:19:12.447
Back to San Francisco.

01:19:12.479 --> 01:19:15.950
Came all of the way down here just to
jump in and swim with the kiddies?

01:19:17.217 --> 01:19:19.820
Very little point
in my trying to explain.

01:19:19.854 --> 01:19:22.457
Well, yeah, I'll buy that.
What about him?

01:19:22.489 --> 01:19:24.792
Him? He's harmless.

01:19:24.826 --> 01:19:28.096
Back in the '60s, he was part of the
free speech movement at Berkeley.

01:19:29.529 --> 01:19:32.065
I think he did
a little too much LDS.

01:19:32.099 --> 01:19:35.103
LDS?

01:19:35.136 --> 01:19:36.938
Come on. Why don't you
let me give you a lift?

01:19:36.970 --> 01:19:40.340
We had our first read-through
at your house on Kashmir.

01:19:40.373 --> 01:19:44.378
And there was... He had the
whales' song playing for us.

01:19:44.412 --> 01:19:47.548
And I knew then how much
this project meant to him

01:19:47.582 --> 01:19:49.184
on a personal level.

01:19:49.216 --> 01:19:51.219
He was trying
to get us to get it,

01:19:51.252 --> 01:19:54.355
which to me, transcends doing
another "Star Trek" film.

01:19:54.387 --> 01:19:58.225
Although, in fact, it actually is what
"Star Trek" has always been about,

01:19:58.259 --> 01:20:01.429
which is meaningful issues
about how to live.

01:20:03.197 --> 01:20:05.567
# Just where is our future?
The things we've done and said #

01:20:05.600 --> 01:20:08.603
# Let's just push the button
We'd be better off dead #

01:20:08.636 --> 01:20:10.505
# 'Cause I hate you #

01:20:10.537 --> 01:20:12.072
Excuse me.

01:20:12.105 --> 01:20:14.509
# And I berate you #

01:20:14.542 --> 01:20:16.177
Excuse me.

01:20:16.210 --> 01:20:18.512
Would you mind
stopping that noise?

01:20:23.050 --> 01:20:25.153
# The only choice we're given
is how many megatons #

01:20:25.185 --> 01:20:26.487
Excuse me.

01:20:26.520 --> 01:20:29.057
Would you mind stopping
that damn noise?

01:20:29.090 --> 01:20:31.391
# And I say screw you #

01:20:31.425 --> 01:20:35.297
# And I hope you're blue too #

01:20:42.670 --> 01:20:46.274
"Star Trek IV" was one of the
highlights of Dad's career,

01:20:46.306 --> 01:20:48.342
really part of the
pinnacle of his career,

01:20:48.376 --> 01:20:51.546
because immediately after that
came "Three Men and a Baby."

01:20:51.578 --> 01:20:53.347
The making
of "Three Men and a Baby"

01:20:53.381 --> 01:20:56.584
was a magical time where everything
came together beautifully.

01:20:56.617 --> 01:20:59.320
I felt enormously fortunate
to be involved with the project.

01:20:59.353 --> 01:21:00.320
Nice job, Pete.

01:21:00.354 --> 01:21:03.324
You know, the "LA Times"
came out with an article

01:21:03.356 --> 01:21:05.292
when that movie came out,
and it was a hit

01:21:05.326 --> 01:21:08.061
the winter season,
the holiday season of '87.

01:21:08.095 --> 01:21:12.166
"LA Times" talked about the fact that the
hit from the previous holiday season

01:21:12.198 --> 01:21:15.369
was a feature film entitled
"Star Trek IV: The Voyage Home,"

01:21:15.403 --> 01:21:18.573
and that both of those films happened
to be directed by the same guy.

01:21:19.539 --> 01:21:20.707
Then came "The Good Mother",

01:21:20.740 --> 01:21:23.912
and my relationship with my
father hit an all-time low.

01:21:23.944 --> 01:21:25.380
And you've left her
alone with him?

01:21:25.412 --> 01:21:28.048
Well, of course I have. She likes
him. They have fun together, Brian.

01:21:28.082 --> 01:21:29.617
Well, ask him about
the fun, Anna.

01:21:29.649 --> 01:21:31.652
Well, what are you suggesting, Brian,
that he did something wrong with Molly?

01:21:31.685 --> 01:21:33.153
- He did, Anna.
- Well, he didn't.

01:21:33.186 --> 01:21:35.256
She told me.
She's told the shrink.

01:21:35.288 --> 01:21:37.024
- He did it, Anna!
- No, Brian, he didn't do it!

01:21:37.057 --> 01:21:38.460
You ask him!
And you let him!

01:21:38.493 --> 01:21:41.195
By the time filming
of "The Good Mother" wrapped,

01:21:41.228 --> 01:21:44.364
I felt the same way I had at the end
of shooting "Three Men and a Baby."

01:21:44.398 --> 01:21:48.569
I thought, "Boy, this could be even more
of a rocket ride than 'Three Men.'"

01:21:48.601 --> 01:21:52.439
And it was a rocket ride,
all right... straight down.

01:21:52.472 --> 01:21:54.274
Box office was disappointing,

01:21:54.307 --> 01:21:58.212
and the film soon disappeared
from the theaters.

01:21:58.244 --> 01:22:02.317
I started drinking
regularly, ritually,

01:22:02.350 --> 01:22:05.553
during probably the second year
or third year of our series.

01:22:05.586 --> 01:22:09.222
The ritual became so ingrained
and so important to me,

01:22:09.256 --> 01:22:13.461
because I looked forward to that release
at the end of the pressure of the day

01:22:13.493 --> 01:22:17.998
with the dialogue, and the pace, and
get 15 pages or 12 pages done today,

01:22:18.032 --> 01:22:19.367
and all of that sort of thing.

01:22:19.399 --> 01:22:22.302
And the minute we finished the
last shot, I would have a drink.

01:22:22.336 --> 01:22:24.238
And then it became
a series of drinks.

01:22:24.270 --> 01:22:26.640
And little by little, before I knew
it, I was drinking more and more

01:22:26.673 --> 01:22:28.676
because my addictive
personality was taking over.

01:22:28.708 --> 01:22:32.579
It was the martinis, you know,
getting a drink when he'd come home,

01:22:32.613 --> 01:22:34.481
having a couple drinks.

01:22:34.515 --> 01:22:38.653
And...you know, while it
made him more relaxed,

01:22:38.685 --> 01:22:41.355
he also shut down.

01:22:41.389 --> 01:22:45.993
The habit grew to the power
that it did in my later years

01:22:46.027 --> 01:22:49.396
because I didn't have that thought, "I'm
young. I still have a distance to go."

01:22:49.430 --> 01:22:53.234
Which is a devilish part
of the disease.

01:22:53.266 --> 01:22:57.104
The 1980's were a very
difficult time for my dad.

01:22:57.137 --> 01:23:00.475
His parents had recently died,
my grandparents,

01:23:00.507 --> 01:23:03.043
within six months of each other.

01:23:03.077 --> 01:23:04.645
My dad was going through
a very complicated

01:23:04.677 --> 01:23:06.514
and difficult divorce
from my mother.

01:23:06.546 --> 01:23:08.615
They had been married
for 32 years.

01:23:08.649 --> 01:23:09.917
It was also about this time

01:23:09.951 --> 01:23:12.686
that there was a lot of
head-banging between the two of us.

01:23:12.720 --> 01:23:15.323
There were a lot of old issues
that were coming up,

01:23:15.355 --> 01:23:18.658
and there were a number
of fights between us.

01:23:18.692 --> 01:23:22.363
He was also drinking. A lot of
this was fueled by alcohol.

01:23:22.395 --> 01:23:25.032
And quite frankly, I was still
getting high at the time,

01:23:25.065 --> 01:23:28.168
and that was certainly not
helping matters between us.

01:23:29.837 --> 01:23:32.273
"There's one major area
that I should touch on

01:23:32.305 --> 01:23:34.274
"before coming to a conclusion,

01:23:34.307 --> 01:23:36.444
"competition with my father.

01:23:36.476 --> 01:23:40.213
"This was easy for me
in strangely painful way.

01:23:40.247 --> 01:23:43.818
"My father never earned
more than a $150 a week.

01:23:43.850 --> 01:23:47.654
"I realize that competition
with me is very tough.

01:23:47.688 --> 01:23:49.757
"I am very loud and verbal.

01:23:49.789 --> 01:23:54.194
"Also I have been very lucky,
made good money, and I'm famous.

01:23:55.395 --> 01:23:56.797
"That's a lot tougher
to deal with

01:23:56.831 --> 01:24:00.235
"than me competing against
150-dollar a week barber."

01:24:02.368 --> 01:24:06.106
A lot of the problems that I had
with my dad were not that dissimilar

01:24:06.140 --> 01:24:08.510
from problems that other
fathers and sons experience.

01:24:10.644 --> 01:24:12.814
The difference is that
my dad was adored

01:24:12.846 --> 01:24:15.817
by millions of fans
all over the world.

01:24:15.850 --> 01:24:21.389
And oftentimes, I felt like I was competing
with them for his love and attention.

01:24:21.421 --> 01:24:26.460
And sometimes, I honestly felt
like I was losing the battle.

01:24:26.493 --> 01:24:30.664
After we would have one of these
incredible knock-down, drag-out fights,

01:24:30.698 --> 01:24:36.604
I would go out into the world and be
confronted by images of Spock everywhere.

01:24:38.338 --> 01:24:41.242
# I want to know
what you're feeling #

01:24:41.274 --> 01:24:44.645
# Tell me what's on your mind #

01:24:52.685 --> 01:24:53.654
Pure energy.

01:24:56.657 --> 01:24:58.359
Pure energy.

01:25:04.765 --> 01:25:08.603
In 1989, Dad and
Susan got married,

01:25:08.636 --> 01:25:11.205
and his domestic life
started to get much better.

01:25:11.238 --> 01:25:13.740
She was a real
stabilizing force for him.

01:25:13.774 --> 01:25:17.145
And he was very happy with her, and
they were very devoted to each other.

01:25:17.177 --> 01:25:20.680
It was at this period of time,
he told me later on,

01:25:20.713 --> 01:25:23.850
that he was really
happy with his life,

01:25:23.884 --> 01:25:28.221
and yet didn't really understand
why he was still drinking.

01:25:28.255 --> 01:25:32.460
And it was at that point that he
started to really, seriously look

01:25:32.493 --> 01:25:34.829
at what was happening
with his life.

01:25:34.862 --> 01:25:38.500
And he made his decision
to go into his own recovery.

01:26:06.560 --> 01:26:09.830
My first images were
photographed with this camera

01:26:09.863 --> 01:26:11.566
and enlarged with this camera

01:26:11.599 --> 01:26:14.635
and with about 20 cents
worth of Kodak supplies.

01:26:14.667 --> 01:26:18.939
And I just became fascinated
with the ability

01:26:18.972 --> 01:26:21.609
to create an image,
something that you could hold,

01:26:21.641 --> 01:26:24.278
an object you could hold in
your hand, and there it is.

01:26:24.310 --> 01:26:25.512
Something I shot this morning,

01:26:25.546 --> 01:26:26.914
and tonight, I have
the picture in my hand.

01:26:26.948 --> 01:26:30.218
I could hang it on my wall, or
give it to my family, or whatever.

01:26:30.251 --> 01:26:31.186
That was the beginning.

01:26:56.042 --> 01:26:59.246
Although Dad started taking
pictures at an early age,

01:26:59.279 --> 01:27:02.250
he continued this hobby
throughout his life.

01:27:02.283 --> 01:27:04.652
He would often take portraits
of me and Julie,

01:27:04.685 --> 01:27:07.989
and some of those ended up in
the poetry books he published.

01:27:52.032 --> 01:27:53.833
James T. Kirk.

01:27:53.867 --> 01:27:56.537
Along came J.J. Abrams

01:27:56.569 --> 01:27:58.572
who found a way
to crack it open

01:27:58.604 --> 01:28:00.807
to an entirely new
and different audience.

01:28:06.613 --> 01:28:09.750
Who the hell am I to tell Leonard
Nimoy what Spock should do?

01:28:09.783 --> 01:28:12.053
But it's my job,
so I'm doing the best I can.

01:28:12.086 --> 01:28:14.454
But I was amazed
at how open he was.

01:28:14.488 --> 01:28:18.626
Leonard was okay with the idea of
this new incarnation of "Star Trek."

01:28:18.658 --> 01:28:24.497
It set a tone on the set even beyond
the days that Leonard was working.

01:28:24.530 --> 01:28:27.033
You didn't have to know
all about "Star Trek."

01:28:27.067 --> 01:28:28.402
You could come
and enjoy this movie

01:28:28.435 --> 01:28:31.372
as a person who had never seen
anything of "Star Trek" before.

01:28:31.404 --> 01:28:32.806
-Fascinating.
-What?

01:28:32.840 --> 01:28:34.408
Okay, I'm sure
you're just doing your job,

01:28:34.440 --> 01:28:36.344
but could you not come
a wee bit sooner?

01:28:36.377 --> 01:28:39.013
Six months I've been here living
off Star Fleet protein nibs

01:28:39.046 --> 01:28:40.881
and the promise of a good meal.

01:28:40.913 --> 01:28:42.381
Myself, Leonard, and Chris
shared a trailer

01:28:42.416 --> 01:28:46.052
when we were shooting the stuff when
they discover Scotty on the planet.

01:28:46.086 --> 01:28:48.823
And it was quite far from the
circus, from the unit base,

01:28:48.855 --> 01:28:52.425
so we had a trailer that
we just sat in, and we shared.

01:28:52.458 --> 01:28:53.827
And we were shooting
really late at night.

01:28:53.860 --> 01:28:55.863
It was, like, you know, 2:00
or 3:00 in the morning.

01:28:55.895 --> 01:28:57.997
And Chris, Leonard, and I
were just sat in this...

01:28:58.030 --> 01:29:01.001
And Leonard was in his
full Spock regalia, ears.

01:29:01.033 --> 01:29:03.536
We had the big sort of like
winter coat on and stuff,

01:29:03.569 --> 01:29:06.539
and he sat upright,
and he went to sleep.

01:29:06.573 --> 01:29:11.011
And he, was just sat there
just quietly snoring.

01:29:11.043 --> 01:29:14.114
And Chris and I were just
looking at each other like,

01:29:14.148 --> 01:29:16.617
"That's Spock, and he snores."

01:29:17.717 --> 01:29:19.753
We were shooting a scene,
and Leonard was walking,

01:29:19.787 --> 01:29:26.694
and he fell... and he landed,
and he cut and broke his nose.

01:29:28.561 --> 01:29:32.766
So the feeling that,
you know, you have

01:29:32.800 --> 01:29:37.070
when someone that you care about as
much as I did, of course, gets hurt,

01:29:37.104 --> 01:29:39.073
it's a horrible feeling.

01:29:39.105 --> 01:29:41.574
When you've wounded Spock...

01:29:41.608 --> 01:29:44.412
you just wanna...
you know, kill yourself.

01:29:44.444 --> 01:29:46.646
It's just... It was...
It was horrible.

01:29:46.680 --> 01:29:49.650
And we're trying to figure out what
we're gonna do for the rest of the day,

01:29:49.682 --> 01:29:52.520
and I hear, like, "No, no, no,
no, we're going to keep going."

01:29:52.552 --> 01:29:53.820
And it was Leonard
who was like,

01:29:53.854 --> 01:29:55.356
"We're just gonna
keep shooting."

01:29:55.389 --> 01:30:00.127
And I'm thinking, "Is he out of his
fucking mind? He just broke his nose."

01:30:00.159 --> 01:30:02.061
And Leonard was like,
"Let's keep going."

01:30:02.095 --> 01:30:04.965
And we finished, and no one
ever heard this story publicly

01:30:04.997 --> 01:30:07.999
until you and I had
this conversation.

01:30:10.938 --> 01:30:12.739
Speak your mind, Spock.

01:30:15.742 --> 01:30:17.711
That would be unwise.

01:30:17.743 --> 01:30:21.047
Mine is a very different
Spock than your dad's.

01:30:21.081 --> 01:30:25.953
I was really fortunate to be able
to explore even more than your dad,

01:30:25.985 --> 01:30:28.456
because as entertainment
evolved,

01:30:28.488 --> 01:30:30.623
as narration evolved,
as story-telling evolved

01:30:30.657 --> 01:30:32.092
over the intervening decades

01:30:32.125 --> 01:30:35.662
between when he created the
role and when I assumed it,

01:30:35.695 --> 01:30:39.699
I think that it opened up
a little bit more space

01:30:39.733 --> 01:30:42.503
for us to get in
and play with that.

01:30:45.771 --> 01:30:47.908
Mr. Spock.

01:30:47.940 --> 01:30:52.479
Sharing that with him, and
discussing it, and exploring it

01:30:52.512 --> 01:30:55.615
through the context
of our personal relationship,

01:30:55.649 --> 01:30:58.853
that was probably one of the most
creatively satisfying aspects

01:30:58.886 --> 01:31:02.856
of assuming a role that had already
been established so firmly

01:31:02.890 --> 01:31:04.859
and created so boldly.

01:31:04.891 --> 01:31:06.193
No pun intended.

01:31:06.226 --> 01:31:11.731
Should I choose to complete the
Vulcan discipline of Kolinahr

01:31:11.765 --> 01:31:13.968
and purge all emotion...

01:31:15.836 --> 01:31:19.173
I trust you will not feel
it reflects judgment upon you.

01:31:21.807 --> 01:31:25.778
Spock...

01:31:25.811 --> 01:31:29.216
as always, whatever
you choose to be...

01:31:30.317 --> 01:31:33.052
you will have a proud mother.

01:31:33.086 --> 01:31:37.123
Every time he goes
into a negative place,

01:31:37.157 --> 01:31:39.293
he starts being a little
bit of a pessimist,

01:31:39.326 --> 01:31:45.599
he allows Uhura and Kirk
to snap him out of it.

01:31:45.631 --> 01:31:47.701
And I really like that.

01:31:47.734 --> 01:31:51.672
He's just... He's a man to me.
Like, Spock is really a man.

01:31:51.704 --> 01:31:53.673
Even though
he's half alien, it's like...

01:31:53.707 --> 01:31:56.911
He could have been...
I don't know, half anything,

01:31:56.944 --> 01:32:00.981
but he's still
very much... natural.

01:32:07.287 --> 01:32:10.224
What do you need? Tell me.

01:32:10.256 --> 01:32:12.125
Tell me.

01:32:12.158 --> 01:32:15.094
I thought that was
a perfect example

01:32:15.127 --> 01:32:17.331
of the evolution
of the character,

01:32:17.363 --> 01:32:19.899
of painting him
in a different light

01:32:19.932 --> 01:32:24.604
and seeing that there is
this capacity for feeling,

01:32:24.637 --> 01:32:27.307
for emotion, for intimacy,
for connection.

01:32:27.341 --> 01:32:29.076
It's still regulated.

01:32:29.109 --> 01:32:32.246
It's still within the
boundaries or the parameters

01:32:32.279 --> 01:32:34.215
of what it means to be Vulcan.

01:32:38.685 --> 01:32:40.087
Father.

01:32:48.395 --> 01:32:50.765
I am not our father.

01:32:57.938 --> 01:33:00.641
There are so few Vulcans left,

01:33:00.673 --> 01:33:03.109
we cannot afford
to ignore each other.

01:33:03.143 --> 01:33:06.913
Spock, in this case,
do yourself a favor.

01:33:08.314 --> 01:33:11.985
Put aside logic.
Do what feels right.

01:33:17.724 --> 01:33:21.028
Since my customary farewell
would appear oddly self-serving,

01:33:21.060 --> 01:33:24.965
I shall simply say... good luck.

01:33:27.833 --> 01:33:29.036
Dad was really happy

01:33:29.069 --> 01:33:31.205
to be in the new incarnation
of "Star Trek."

01:33:31.238 --> 01:33:34.008
It was a high point for him.

01:33:34.041 --> 01:33:36.976
But much like Spock's
problems with his father,

01:33:37.010 --> 01:33:39.913
my relationship with my father
was still very troubled.

01:33:39.945 --> 01:33:42.315
My first officer,
Commander Spock.

01:33:42.349 --> 01:33:44.083
Vulcan honors us
with your presence.

01:33:44.117 --> 01:33:45.820
We come to serve.

01:33:48.954 --> 01:33:50.858
Your service honors us,
Captain.

01:33:50.890 --> 01:33:52.192
Thank you.

01:33:55.362 --> 01:33:59.800
Around 2006, we were just about
completely estranged from one another.

01:33:59.832 --> 01:34:02.402
Old issues were flaring up.

01:34:02.435 --> 01:34:05.104
And, I was at a low
point in my life.

01:34:05.137 --> 01:34:07.140
I had just ended
an 18-year marriage,

01:34:07.173 --> 01:34:11.444
and I had decided to go
into my own 12-step recovery.

01:34:11.478 --> 01:34:14.181
And it was a real difficult
time for the two of us.

01:34:14.213 --> 01:34:15.948
And basically,
for three or four years,

01:34:15.981 --> 01:34:18.051
we had very, very
little communication.

01:34:18.085 --> 01:34:22.823
By around 2008, we started to
talk again, and reconnect again,

01:34:22.855 --> 01:34:26.826
and really came back together in
our relationship with each other.

01:34:30.229 --> 01:34:34.734
I had met Martha in a doctor's
office, and she was...

01:34:34.768 --> 01:34:36.069
She was my age,

01:34:36.103 --> 01:34:41.375
and she was very sweet,
fun, attractive woman,

01:34:41.408 --> 01:34:43.744
and I started dating
her regularly.

01:34:43.777 --> 01:34:46.079
And I mean, I was
so much happier having Martha

01:34:46.113 --> 01:34:48.282
that I married her.

01:34:51.051 --> 01:34:53.287
Four and a half months
after we were married,

01:34:53.319 --> 01:34:56.157
Martha was diagnosed
with terminal cancer.

01:35:08.167 --> 01:35:09.402
The weird thing was for me,

01:35:09.435 --> 01:35:12.305
and I was really kind of conscious
of it now in retrospect,

01:35:12.338 --> 01:35:17.778
was that in 2004,
when I left my 18-year marriage,

01:35:17.810 --> 01:35:20.246
and moved out of my house, and
left my kids behind for one.

01:35:20.279 --> 01:35:22.315
I mean, it was
a real low point in my life.

01:35:22.349 --> 01:35:25.918
I didn't even call my dad. He wasn't even
on the list, because of our period of,

01:35:25.952 --> 01:35:28.355
you know, beginning of
the estrangement period.

01:35:28.387 --> 01:35:32.425
But when I was able to
pull myself back together,

01:35:32.458 --> 01:35:34.461
after I got that phone call
from the doctor,

01:35:34.493 --> 01:35:37.029
the first phone call I made...

01:35:37.063 --> 01:35:38.498
Was to your dad.

01:35:41.268 --> 01:35:44.137
I just... It still.
It just overwhelms me now

01:35:44.171 --> 01:35:47.240
that we could get to that point
where he could be my go-to guy.

01:35:47.274 --> 01:35:48.309
Yeah.

01:35:48.341 --> 01:35:49.976
And in the next 18 months
of my life with Martha,

01:35:50.010 --> 01:35:55.349
which were, you know, probably the most
challenging possibly in my entire life,

01:35:55.381 --> 01:35:58.918
my dad and Susan were there
every step of the way

01:35:58.952 --> 01:36:01.288
to support me
and keep me going.

01:36:03.957 --> 01:36:08.561
And after that, my dad and I
never again... looked back

01:36:08.595 --> 01:36:12.132
at the wreckage
from our past, ever.

01:36:16.936 --> 01:36:20.439
"So here we are.
You're a man, an individual,

01:36:20.472 --> 01:36:24.344
"very bright, talented,
goal-oriented, sensitive,

01:36:24.377 --> 01:36:27.447
"and a lot of other good things.

01:36:27.479 --> 01:36:31.484
"Above all, I want you to know
that you are priceless to me.

01:36:31.518 --> 01:36:35.122
I'm proud of you, and I deeply
love you. Your father."

01:36:46.399 --> 01:36:49.436
My life has become much,
much more about family.

01:36:49.469 --> 01:36:52.038
I used to... The way
I describe it now was

01:36:52.072 --> 01:36:55.976
I used to major in career
and minor in family.

01:36:56.009 --> 01:36:57.210
And now, I've turned it around.

01:36:57.243 --> 01:37:00.112
I'm much more majoring in
family and minoring in career.

01:37:00.145 --> 01:37:03.149
I do an occasional pop-up thing
here and there for friends,

01:37:03.182 --> 01:37:04.952
but mostly, I'm dealing
with my family.

01:37:04.984 --> 01:37:08.421
With dad marrying
our step-mom, Susan,

01:37:08.454 --> 01:37:11.490
she and Aaron became
a part of our family.

01:37:11.524 --> 01:37:15.262
She was great in the fact
that she showed Dad

01:37:15.295 --> 01:37:18.131
that being with your children
and your grandchildren,

01:37:18.163 --> 01:37:21.068
it's very important.

01:37:21.100 --> 01:37:23.871
You need to be a part
of their life.

01:37:23.904 --> 01:37:26.974
And let's bring
everybody together.

01:37:27.006 --> 01:37:29.408
Let's... Let's have
a big family unit,

01:37:29.442 --> 01:37:31.177
and we have a big family.

01:37:32.612 --> 01:37:34.347
In the last years of his life
were the times that

01:37:34.381 --> 01:37:35.548
the family got together
at the house

01:37:35.582 --> 01:37:40.320
for any variety of occasions
from birthdays to holidays.

01:37:40.353 --> 01:37:42.288
Leonard was a very
even-keeled guy.

01:37:42.322 --> 01:37:43.923
He didn't always show
a lot of emotion

01:37:43.957 --> 01:37:49.630
but I'd say those times at which he would
toast the family at those gatherings

01:37:49.662 --> 01:37:53.900
were the times I maybe saw
him express the most emotion.

01:37:53.934 --> 01:37:56.136
He was so grateful
to have everybody there.

01:37:56.168 --> 01:37:58.537
He was grateful to feel the love
from everybody that was there.

01:37:58.570 --> 01:38:03.010
And he was grateful to be able to
love the family the way that he did

01:38:03.042 --> 01:38:04.944
and provide for the family
the way that he could.

01:38:34.173 --> 01:38:37.677
The day Leonard died, I...

01:38:37.711 --> 01:38:39.646
He was in a coma,

01:38:39.679 --> 01:38:43.250
and I, leaned over
and said to him...

01:38:51.323 --> 01:38:53.960
"You made the world
stand up and listen."

01:38:55.095 --> 01:38:57.664
And I'd swear
he nodded his head.

01:41:39.158 --> 01:41:42.194
What I admired about Leonard

01:41:42.228 --> 01:41:46.666
was his willingness
to love his family,

01:41:46.698 --> 01:41:50.636
and because I was on the periphery
of it, I got that love.

01:41:50.670 --> 01:41:53.739
It made him a wonderful actor
in the work we did.

01:41:53.773 --> 01:41:56.243
And I think it
made him a mensch,

01:41:56.275 --> 01:41:58.144
probably a word you're
going to hear a lot.

01:41:58.177 --> 01:41:59.613
Mensch.

01:41:59.645 --> 01:42:05.317
A mensch is someone who's
responsible, and disciplined,

01:42:05.350 --> 01:42:06.585
and you can count on.

01:42:06.618 --> 01:42:09.322
He was just this
stable force in my life,

01:42:09.354 --> 01:42:11.457
and I knew I could
always count on him.

01:42:11.490 --> 01:42:13.894
He was the mensch of mensches.

01:42:13.926 --> 01:42:18.697
He was loved and adored by,
I think, everybody on the set.

01:42:18.730 --> 01:42:24.403
To create a character who
leaves a mark on the society,

01:42:24.436 --> 01:42:27.740
that strikes a chord
that resonates,

01:42:27.774 --> 01:42:29.709
Leonard Nimoy did that.

